Step-by-Step Guide: Prometheus + Grafana Monitoring

Step 1 — Connect to Your EC2 DevOps Machine

Login to the EC2 instance where you installed:

Docker

Terraform

kubectl

AWS CLI


Run:

ssh -i your-key.pem ubuntu@EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Verify cluster access:

kubectl get nodes

Expected output:

ip-10-0-1-12   Ready
ip-10-0-2-15   Ready

This confirms EKS cluster is connected.


---

Step 2 — Create Monitoring Namespace

To organize monitoring components, create a namespace.

kubectl create namespace monitoring

Verify:

kubectl get ns

You should see:

monitoring
default
kube-system


---

Step 3 — Install Node Exporter

What Node Exporter Does

Node Exporter collects:

CPU usage

Memory usage

Disk utilization

Network I/O


It runs on every worker node using DaemonSet.


---

Create Node Exporter File

Create file:

mkdir -p k8s/monitoring
cd k8s/monitoring
nano node-exporter.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: node-exporter
  namespace: monitoring
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: node-exporter

  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: node-exporter

    spec:
      containers:
      - name: node-exporter
        image: prom/node-exporter:latest

        ports:
        - containerPort: 9100


---

Apply Node Exporter

kubectl apply -f node-exporter.yaml

Verify:

kubectl get pods -n monitoring

Example output:

node-exporter-abc12   Running
node-exporter-xj912   Running

This means Node exporter running on each node.


---

Step 4 — Create Node Exporter Service

Prometheus must access Node Exporter.

Create:

nano node-exporter-service.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: node-exporter
  namespace: monitoring

spec:
  selector:
    app: node-exporter

  ports:
  - port: 9100
    targetPort: 9100

Apply:

kubectl apply -f node-exporter-service.yaml


---

Step 5 — Install Prometheus

Prometheus collects and stores metrics.


---

Create Prometheus ConfigMap

Create:

nano prometheus-config.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: prometheus-config
  namespace: monitoring

data:
  prometheus.yml: |
    global:
      scrape_interval: 15s

    scrape_configs:

      - job_name: 'node-exporter'
        static_configs:
          - targets: ['node-exporter:9100']

Apply:

kubectl apply -f prometheus-config.yaml


---

Step 6 — Deploy Prometheus

Create:

nano prometheus-deployment.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: prometheus
  namespace: monitoring

spec:
  replicas: 1

  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: prometheus

  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: prometheus

    spec:
      containers:
      - name: prometheus
        image: prom/prometheus

        ports:
        - containerPort: 9090

        volumeMounts:
        - name: config-volume
          mountPath: /etc/prometheus

      volumes:
      - name: config-volume
        configMap:
          name: prometheus-config

Apply:

kubectl apply -f prometheus-deployment.yaml

Check:

kubectl get pods -n monitoring


---

Step 7 — Expose Prometheus Service

Create:

nano prometheus-service.yaml

Paste:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: prometheus-service
  namespace: monitoring

spec:
  type: NodePort

  selector:
    app: prometheus

  ports:
  - port: 9090
    targetPort: 9090
    nodePort: 30090

Apply:

kubectl apply -f prometheus-service.yaml


---

Step 8 — Access Prometheus Dashboard

Find node IP:

kubectl get nodes -o wide

Example:

3.92.11.21

Open browser:

http://3.92.11.21:30090

Go to:

Status → Targets

You should see:

node-exporter
UP

